{"key":"post-15325666","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>15325666</id>\n<content>Two things.&amp;nbsp; Do NOT colonize your jars in a 'chamber', whether it's heated or not.&amp;nbsp; Leave them on an open shelf exposed to ambient air currents.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Secondly, 69F is fine.&amp;nbsp; If it gets down below 60F, run a space heater near them, but not pumped into a tub or other chamber.&amp;nbsp; The best bet is to put them on the top shelf of a book shelf.&amp;nbsp; It's always warmer higher in a room than down low, and there's fewer contaminants high up as well, since contaminant spores will naturally sink to the ground because of gravity.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I've colonized jars at 40F in the refrigerator just to prove it can work.&amp;nbsp; It's slower, taking about 2 months to colonize a 1 quart jar, but that's better than ruining them with excess heat.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>15328840</next>\n<prev>15325429</prev>\n<first>15325315</first>\n<last>15333815</last>\n<when>1320501773</when>\n<utime>11/05/11 05:02 PM</utime>\n</post>"}